{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-tsx","path":"/texts/tipitaka/sutta-pitaka/samyutta-nikaya/SN2/magadha-sutta/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>At Sāvatthī.</p>\n<p>Standing to one side, the god Māgadha addressed the Buddha in verse:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>“How many lamps are there, <br>\nto shine their light on the world? <br>\nWe’ve come to ask the Buddha; <br>\nhow are we to understand this?” <br>\n<br>\n“There are four lamps in the world, <br>\na fifth is not found. <br>\nThe sun shines by day, <br>\nthe moon glows at night, <br>\n<br>\nwhile a fire burns both <br>\nby day and by night. <br>\nBut a Buddha is the best of lights: <br>\nthis is the supreme radiance.”</p>\n</blockquote>\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<p><a href=\"/texts/tipitaka/sutta-pitaka/samyutta-nikaya/SN2/damali-sutta/\">SN.2.5. Dāmali Sutta (“With Dāmali”)</a></p>\n</div>","htmlAst":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"At Sāvatthī."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Standing to one side, the god Māgadha addressed the Buddha in verse:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"blockquote","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"“How many lamps are there, "},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","properties":{},"children":[]},{"type":"text","value":"\nto shine their light on the world? "},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","properties":{},"children":[]},{"type":"text","value":"\nWe’ve come to ask the Buddha; "},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","properties":{},"children":[]},{"type":"text","value":"\nhow are we to understand this?” "},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","properties":{},"children":[]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","properties":{},"children":[]},{"ty